				<td colspan="2"><span>No game, no matter how hard any designer tries is ever &quot;balanced&quot;.  If a game were &quot;balanced&quot; then it would be absolutely boring, because every class would be able to succeed at every task without the benifit of any other different class.  That is absolutely not the case.
<br />

<br />
I tried a game that was designed using the &quot;different but equal&quot; philosophy.  Classes were balanced, but unfortunately they were all basically the same, and all basically boring.  You may have heard of it, it was &quot;Horizons&quot;.
<br />

<br />
I also tried a game that was designed so that the classes were pretty much mutually supporting, absolutely dependent on one another for survival.  A great feature of this game was also its &quot;ease of play&quot;.  Unfortunately &quot;ease of play&quot; means that the game is not even challenging for my 10 year old, which definately removes the fun after about a week.  Though visually stunning, being blinded by beauty only lasts so long.  You may have heard of it, it was &quot;City of Heroes&quot;.
<br />

<br />
I tried a game that was focused on item decay and evolving player driven storyline.  This game was interesting enough to hold my attention for a good long time, because the classes worked very well with each other, but every class was able to play on their own as well.  The classes were very unbalanced however, and the prime hunting areas were very log jammed, and overall the game world was quite small.  Item decay was very expensive, and quite a bit of time was spent on keeping gear in tip top shape, becuase to do well in the game it had to be.  Unfortunately this game was run by a company that accepts nothing less than market domination in its games, and just when a major retail expansion could have been used to expand the game, fix alot of problems and advance the storyline, it was dumped.  You may have heard of it, it was &quot;Earth and Beyond&quot;.
<br />

<br />
Plain fact is that many games have tried to do things &quot;better&quot; than EQ.  To correct all of these &quot;problems&quot; that you have highlighted.  None of them are doing particularly well, and none of them have advanced beyond the &quot;niche&quot; market.  EQ provides a diverse environment, but changing its basic substance to &quot;balance&quot; the classes should not be a priority.  Beyond all other games what EQ is really about is the people, not the gear.</span></td>
