				<td colspan="2"><span>A troll?  Little hairy guy under a bridge?  No....
<br />

<br />
I didn't make  this post to be a sensationalist.  I made it, because I thought bards might enjoy an opportunity to see things from a different perspective -- thereby balancing themselves.  Apparently, all are content to leave well enough alone, and allow people with no earthly grasp of music or barding to dictate their class.
<br />

<br />
My first point was not meant to be exclusive to bards, necessarily.  I agree that melee, and caster skills could also decay.  Annoying?  Yes.  Realistic?  A bit.  OMG!  (reaches for his troll-bat)
<br />

<br />
After having played Diablo 2 for a very long time, and seeing what the developers did to improve the game, I noticed the following:
<br />

<br />
1.  Rather than improving monster AI, they would increase hit points.
<br />

<br />
2.  Rather than allowing a sliding scale for things like magic find, they would instigate a hard cap (or a cap with such diminishing returns, as to make it rediculous).
<br />

<br />
3.  Rather than having customer service, they chose a complete &quot;hands-off&quot; policy.  
<br />

<br />
This third was the greatest shock to me when I came to EQ.  Wow, there are GMs, and you can SEE them!  It is apparent to me, that due to the large amount of money that EQ generates, SOE is interested in keeping its customers.  With all of the improvements that have been demanded, and asked for nicely for bards, it seemed sensible to me to make some concessions in return.  I don't think we're underpowered.  I don't think we're greatly overpowered either, but if half of the changes proposed go live, we may well be, and be dealt a crippling blow with the dreaded nerf-bat.
<br />

<br />
If you don't agree, that is certainly your right.  Perhaps now you at least understand the reason.</span></td>
